<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-826-662  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 826 662.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Sept 3 1990 v9 n18 p108(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Future is bright for government info. technology.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dornan, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Document ProcessingInformation SystemsBudgetingManagement DevelopmentUpgradingAutomationInformation Resources ManagementTrends.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Developments and documents. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Future Is Bright For Government Info.andP;  TechnologyandM;In May, when Federal Sources Inc. presented its forecast for informationtechnology spending, there was considerable skepticism about our optimism.andM;We projected spending in fiscal 1991 to be $20.5 billion, a $2 billionincrease from fiscal 1990.andP;  Tom Hewitt, Federal Sources' president, thenpresented the likely scenario that growth will continue strong through fiscal1995.andP;  Some in the audience wondered what we have been smoking.andM;Clearly there are some difficult times ahead for certain agencies andprograms.andP;  Defense consolidation of facilities, elimination of redundantsystems, and poorly managed or implemented programs will result in somecasualties.andP;  But we see little slack in agency plans for major procurementsin the near future.andM;In July, the Office of Management and Budge published &quot;Management Prioritiesfor the 1992 Budget&quot; (Bulletin M-90-05).andP;  This bulltin guides agencies on theallocation of scarce resources in fiscal 1992.andP;  OMB also lists its toppriorities to improve government management.andP;  Of the seven items listed, fourinvolve improvements in the use of information technology, automation andupgrades to systems.andP;  The remaining three implicitly need greater applicationof information technology to produce the desired improvements.andM;The message is clear.andP;  Agencies need to allocate resources to ensure theeffective application of information technology -- even at the expense ofother needs.andP;  On this issue, OMB is preaching to the choir.andP;  In fact,agencies have been taking this attitude for some time -- without prompting.andM;When Congress slashed $93 million from the Navy's IRM budget, the Navy usedfunds from aircraft and ship maintenance to compnsate.andP;  Congress, in itsinn-nite wisdom, is trying to prevent this kind of reprogramming, however.andM;Agency commitment to information techology, coupled with high-level pressurefrom OMB, makes the future look bright.andP;  We still believe that the federalinformation technology industry is full of opportunities and growth.andM;Bob Dornan is vice president of Federal Sources Inc., Vienna, Va.andO;</TEXT></DOC>